blicProfile?language=EN>Quipper</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/13/02 12:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=335.topic>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Hi Spacetravellers</span><hr size=1> I am intrigued about aliens.....do you think there is a more advanced life form out there somewhere? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MegaLipidCephaloid</span><br>  Posts: 390<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/13/02 1:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=335.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Hi Spacetravellers</span><hr size=1> Yes, but I am just visiting.<br>
<br>
<br>
But more seriously, in a universe of ~100,000,000,000 galaxies each containing maybe 100,000,000,000 suns, it would seem almost inevitable.<br>
<br>
Contrary to that are two facts.<br>
1) It took almost 4 billion years for intelligent life to appear on Earth - making it a rare and unlikely event.<br>
2) As Enrico Fermi said, &quot;Where are they&quot;. Even spreading at slow sub-c expansion, any intelligent life would have comepletely spread thru the galaxy. Either they missed us in time, intelligent civilizations have short lifespans,  they are hiding, or we simply don't recognize them.<br>
<br>
<br>
What do you think?<br>
<br>
<br>
