 <p>"Every man has a right to his opinion, but no man has a right to be wrong in his facts." Bernard Baruch </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 722<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/13/02 6:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=335.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Hi Spacetravellers</span><hr size=1> I like the time explanation... after all, how long have we as a civilization had radio communication?  100 years or less (too lazy to check)?  100 years in 4 billion is a tiny tiny percentage. (too lazy to calculate).<br>
<br>
Also, I wonder if the dinosaurs model of life may be more likely than us hairless monkeys.  If it hadn't been for a big rock, then maybe a saurian claw would be typing this message instead... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1796<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/13/02 11:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=335.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Why aren't they here?</span><hr size=1> Ofcourse there is also the argument that an intelligent lifeform need not necessarily be driven to conquer space. Dolphins are nearly as intelligent as us apes but have no interest in technology that we can discern. Our apparently unique dependancy on complex technologies is a result of our environment shaping us to require it. The universe might be full of intelligent beings with little or no interest in spaceflight. Our own pitiful contributions to spaceflight in the form of an ever decreasing annual budget could easily place us in that category.<br>
<br>
Then there is the problem of crossing interstellar space. I personally believe there is no way of getting past the light barrier and only the most advanced spacefaring species can even get close to it. Warp drives are just a pipedream, in my opinion, but thats just me and most scientists are divided on the subject.<br>
<br>
Sublight velocities are sufficient for any spacefaring species to have colonised the entire Galaxy in theory but real life is full of irksome little unexpected problems. As an example Humans now inhabit virtually every habitable part of the Earths surface. It took time but ancient peoples gradually found their way to every corner of the Earth. Over time they adapted to the particular environment they had made home. Frequently they fought off or were overwhelmed by successive waves of other peoples. As transportation improved these clashes intensified. This is one species fighting amongst itself. Imagine what might happen if totally Alien species met going in different directions. Just as exploration and colonisation was hampered by previous tenants such as the American Red Indian and Australian Aborigine you can expect galactic colonisation to suffer similar slowdowns. <br>
<br>
I like to think there aren't many intelligent civilisations out there. That would mean we have a reasonably good chance of staking a claim on a sizable part of this galaxy before meeting something on a level close to our own. Unlike many people today I do not ascribe to the theory that intelligence equates with friendliness. The top dog of any planet most likely didn't get there by being friendly, trusting or merciful. As far as mother nature is concerned mercy is truly for the weak.  <br>
<br>
My favourite explanation for why intelligent Alien species have not visited us yet is that they are too busy fighting one another.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 8/13/02 11:46:20 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/14/02 6:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=335.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Hi Spacetravellers</span><hr size=1> Even though I'll probably eat my words, I suspect there's no more than one or two spacefaring civilizations in any given galaxy.  &quot;Lower&quot; life might be abundant but I'm not so confident that life has a propensity to develop high intelligence.  Even on our planet there's only a handful of highly intelligent beasts out of millions of different species.  And of all of those critters only one has actually gone on to launch anything beyond Earth.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A> at: 8/14/02 6:53:42 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 746<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/14/02 8:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=335.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=le