that this could extend into millions of years, however, except under very unusual conditions. Iron and steel buildings are doomed in short order (geologically speaking) without intelligent maintenance (and possibly with it). <br>
<br>
After 100 <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> million</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> years, there would be very few outward signs that a civilization had ever existed, though detailed research would soon uncover compelling evidence, like fired brick or cut stone embedded in sedimentary or recent igneous formations. Large metal artifacts (ships?) that had been buried suddenly might also be recognizable as coherent patterns of embedded oxide if the surrounding formation had not been subject to morphological stress. In geologically stable areas like the Canadian Shield; some substructure, like building foundations, might survive that long; and these could conceivably shelter more fragile artifacts. <br>
<br>
Beyond that, it is hard to say, but I believe that a few artifacts would survive in some recognizable form for the entire astronomical lifetime of a planet, but these would be very rare, probably deeply buried, and therefore quite difficult to find.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=stilgar>Stilgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 37<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/15/02 12:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=335.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: 50,000 years</span><hr size=1> What about non-terestrial artifacts?  Surely a civilization <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> more</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> advanced than our own would have left satelites in geosynchronous orbits(what kind of orbit decay times are we talking about?), at a lagrange point, or on the moon.. mars even.  Martian geological activity is negligible, though thte dust storms are pretty harsh.  The moon, obviously, has no weathering agents except for meteor bombardment.  How long does it take for the moon's surface to get reworked completely?  a couple hundred million years?<br>
