<br>
The context of PO's question was our own civilization, which has, as yet, produced relatively few extraterrestrial artifacts but this is an area of real hope for preserving some remnant of our civilization. Ionizing radiation has some erosive effect on metal, but meteorite studies suggest that it might take millions of years for this to cause the complete disintegration of a sizable object. The very light structure of existing satellites would be a factor here. I am not sure about geostationary orbit decay times, but it seems likely that these are very long indeed, also possibly in the millions of years. The surface of the moon is geologically inert for any practical purpose. Radiation and micrometeoroid bombardment would be the only sources of erosion, so even a fairly fragile object can be preserved intact for a very long time in the open. In some sort of rock shelter, this would extend indefinitely, with a large meteor collision as the only hazard. All of the moon's surface has been altered by catastrophic impact at one time or another, but much of this dates from the very early days of the moon's existence, when meteor collisions were much more common than they are today. Some of these areas have remained untouched for billions of years. It therefore seems likely that artifacts in caves or tunnels on the moon would remain intact for the remaining lifetime of the Solar System. If we construct stone or &quot;mooncrete&quot; buildings in the open, these too have a fair chance of surviving that long.     <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showPrevMessage?topicID=335.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showNextMessage?topicID=335.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromW